==Criteria== 
#Functional: The system needs to do its job -- capture and store rainwater from the roof, not leak or have components break, and reduce well water usage. 
# Non-intrusive: The system needs to be out of the way of winery operations. 
# Aesthetically pleasing: The system must blend in with the natural environment, especially so the neighbors will not be able to see it.
# Durable: The rainwater catchment system must be able to withstand the most severe environmental conditions (e.g. strong winds, torrential rains, falling branches, etc.).

==Design==
When building a rainwater catchment system, it is important to consider numerous concepts that are critical to making a system work. Some of these include: installing a first flush system to divert the first 10 minutes of rainwater to prevent contamination by birds, dust and industry (Mollison, 166); constructing an overflow valve for excess rainwater (Mother); and selecting a closed container for storing water. We are not discussing aspects regarding roof and gutters because they are already installed, but it is important to make sure that the gutters for the roof have been cleaned and cleared of debris.

